<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1884-04-17T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1884-04-17T00:00:00-05:00" n="357" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d357">
                    <head>No. 357.<lb/><hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Frelinghuysen</persName> to Mr. <persName type="to">Reed</persName>.</hi></head>
                    <opener><seg rendition="#center">[Extract.]</seg></opener>
                    <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Department
                                    of State</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1884-04-17"><hi rend="italic">April</hi> 17,
                            1884</date>.</dateline>
                        <seg rendition="#left">No. 163.]</seg></opener>
                    <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: Referring to instruction No. 145 of the 21st
                        ultimo, I inclose a a copy of a note<note n="*" xml:id="d357fn1">For
                            inclosures see documents numbered 365 and 366.</note> to the Spanish
                        minister here, touching the request of the consul of Spain at Baltimore to
                        be furnished with certificates of cargoes imported from Cuba, &amp;c., and
                        of the answer<note n="*" xml:id="d357fn2">For inclosures see documents
                            numbered 365 and 366.</note> thereto. * * * *</p>
                    <p>I am, &amp;c.</p>
                    <closer><signed>FRED’K T. FRELINGHUYSEN.</signed></closer>
                </div>
                </body></text></TEI>